      "side": 1,
      "message": "it\u0027s only \u0027generic\u0027 in the sense where the hardware doesn\u0027t know about it. They\u0027re not really part of a base class or anything like that. What I mean is that if, in OOP, you have something like:\n\n   class BaseFoo {\n   ...\n       void save(Stream* stream);\n   ...\n   };\n\n   class Foo : public BaseFoo {\n   ...\n       void save(Stream* stream) {\n           BaseFoo::save(stream);\n           ... save other fields here.\n       }\n   };\n\nWhere it makes sense to write the fields of the base class before those of the derived one. However, I don\u0027t think this really applies here, because the Pipe state isn\u0027t really a \u0027base class\u0027 for HwPipe anymore. On the other hand, every Pipe instance has an associated HwPipe, even if it isn\u0027t associated with a service yet.\n\nWe could say that HwPipe is a \u0027base class\u0027 for Pipe, except that we don\u0027t want to tie the layout/implementation of HwPipe into the Pipe one. What do you think ?",
